    {
      "title": "Synonyms and antonyms in context",
      "html": "<p>A <b>synonym</b> is a word close in meaning to another (<i>begin ~ commence</i>). An <b>antonym</b> is a word of opposite meaning (<i>brave ↔ cowardly</i>). English rarely offers perfect synonyms — the right choice depends on <i>context, register</i> and <i>connotation</i>.</p>\n      <ul>\n        <li><b>Connotation</b>: <i>childish</i> (negative) vs <i>childlike</i> (positive) — both mean 'like a child'.</li>\n        <li><b>Register</b>: <i>buy</i> (neutral), <i>purchase</i> (formal), <i>cop</i> (slang).</li>\n        <li><b>Collocation</b>: we say <i>strong tea</i> and <i>heavy rain</i> — not <i>powerful tea</i>.</li>\n      </ul>\n      <p>Tip: read the whole sentence before choosing a synonym. Test each option in the gap and check that the tone, part of speech and collocation all fit.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Choose the closest in meaning to <i>reluctant</i> in: <i>She was reluctant to answer.</i>",
          "a": "<b>unwilling</b> — the sentence shows hesitation to speak, not fear or dislike."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Register — Agriculture, Sports, Law",
      "html": "<p><b>Register</b> is the specialised vocabulary of a subject or profession. Recognising register helps you follow a passage and pick precise answers.</p>\n      <h4>Agriculture</h4>\n      <ul><li><i>arable, fallow, pasture, tuber, weeding, harvest, silo, irrigation, manure, husbandry, seedling, transplanting.</i></li></ul>\n      <h4>Sports</h4>\n      <ul><li><i>referee, umpire, offside, penalty, sprint, marathon, coach, tactics, halftime, knockout, draw, fixture, dribble, tackle.</i></li></ul>\n      <h4>Law</h4>\n      <ul><li><i>plaintiff, defendant, prosecution, verdict, acquit, convict, bail, adjourn, appeal, testimony, evidence, jurisdiction, judgment, litigation.</i></li></ul>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Which register does <i>plaintiff, defendant, verdict</i> belong to?",
          "a": "Law — these are court-room terms."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Contextual meaning in passages",
      "html": "<p>Comprehension questions often test what a word or phrase means <i>as used in the passage</i>. That may differ from its dictionary meaning.</p>\n      <ol>\n        <li>Read the whole sentence — sometimes two sentences before and after.</li>\n        <li>Ask what idea the sentence is trying to convey; the word must fit that idea.</li>\n        <li>Substitute each option in the sentence. Reject any that changes the meaning or grammar.</li>\n        <li>Beware of <i>look-alike</i> words that sound similar but mean something different.</li>\n      </ol>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "In <i>Her sharp reply silenced the class</i>, <i>sharp</i> means:",
          "a": "<b>quick and cutting</b> (not literally pointed)."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
